{{short description|2001 book by Mark Colyvan}} {{Infobox book | name = The Indispensability of Mathematics | author = [[Mark Colyvan]] | image = The Indispensability of Mathematics.jpg | subject = [[Philosophy of mathematics]] | published = 2001 | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | pages = 192 pp. | isbn = 9780195137545 }}
'''''The Indispensability of Mathematics''''' is a 2001 book by [[Mark Colyvan]] in which he examines the [[Quine–Putnam indispensability thesis]] in the [[philosophy of mathematics]]. This thesis is based on the premise that mathematical entities are placed on the same ontological foundation as other theoretical entities indispensable to our best [[scientific theories]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Melia |first1=Joseph |title=Mark Colyvan, The Indispensability of Mathematics. |journal=Metascience |date=March 2003 |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=55-58 |url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1023%2FA%3A1024411117330}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cole |first1=J. |title=Review: The Indispensability of Mathematics |journal=Mind |date=1 March 2003 |volume=112 |issue=446 |pages=331–336 |doi=10.1093/mind/112.446.331 |url=https://academic.oup.com/mind/article-abstract/112/446/331/990943 |accessdate=26 October 2018 |language=en |issn=0026-4423}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cheyne |first1=C. |title=The Indispensability of Mathematics |journal=Australasian Journal of Philosophy |date=September 2002 |volume=80 |issue=3 |pages=378–379 |doi=10.1080/713659474 |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/713659474 |accessdate=26 October 2018 |language=en |issn=0004-8402}}</ref>
